WEBVTT

00:01.400 --> 00:02.920
Previously on St Elsewhere.

00:02.920 --> 00:04.240
# Dancin' in the street! #

00:04.240 --> 00:06.520
St Eligius' 50th anniversary party.

00:06.520 --> 00:08.400
The founder and chief administrator

00:08.400 --> 00:12.200
of St Eligius Hospital,
Father Joseph McCabe.

00:12.200 --> 00:14.520
     I don't like you, McCabe.

00:14.520 --> 00:16.239
  You're a smoothie from Southie.

00:16.239 --> 00:19.920
And you're a petty bureaucrat
who uses the power of
  the Catholic Church

00:19.920 --> 00:21.600
as if Jesus Christ was your idea.

00:21.600 --> 00:23.720
When did you arrive at St Eligius?

00:23.720 --> 00:25.120
1965.

00:25.120 --> 00:27.600
Excuse me, chaps.
I'm reporting for work.

00:27.600 --> 00:30.160
Tell me about when you were
named Director of Medicine.

00:30.160 --> 00:31.880
Tell me about when you were
named Director of Medicine.
That was 1975.

00:31.880 --> 00:32.840
That's my wife.

00:32.840 --> 00:36.360
That's my wife.
If it's her time,
you've got to let her go.

00:36.360 --> 00:37.560
Breathe, sweetheart.

00:37.560 --> 00:38.600
Won't you hop on to the bed?

00:38.600 --> 00:39.920
Won't you hop on to the bed?
I can't move my legs.

00:39.920 --> 00:43.040
The O'Caseys never had
much to pass on except hope.

00:43.040 --> 00:44.640
And a family name.

00:44.640 --> 00:46.920
Now that's going to stop
with our son Kevin.

00:46.920 --> 00:47.960
Why?

00:47.960 --> 00:49.040
He's homosexual.

00:49.040 --> 00:50.480
I came by cos I'm concerned.

00:50.480 --> 00:53.160
All right, you're concerned.  Fine.

00:53.160 --> 00:57.160
What are you doing with my son?
Pete! Where are you going? Pete!

02:24.520 --> 02:27.760
What's the use of plain by the rules
if you're never going to win?

02:27.760 --> 02:30.600
Donny, winning isn't
the only thing that counts.

02:30.600 --> 02:33.840
We all have to play by the rules,
otherwise everybody loses.

02:33.840 --> 02:35.920
George Deayton cheats at marbles.

02:35.920 --> 02:37.160
             He does?

02:37.160 --> 02:41.160
Today, plus a swirly, two aggies!

02:42.840 --> 02:44.600
And my favourite shooter!

02:44.600 --> 02:47.840
Listen, son, there's no real
satisfaction unless we play fair

02:47.840 --> 02:51.360
and square and do our best all
the time. Why don't you challenge him

02:51.360 --> 02:53.720
to another game tomorrow?
Maybe you'll win.

02:53.720 --> 02:55.520
Or lose all my marbles.

02:55.520 --> 02:56.440
                       Father McCabe!

02:56.440 --> 02:57.680
                       Father McCabe!
How are you, my friend?

02:57.680 --> 03:00.440
Fine. My wife and I really enjoyed
the sermon Sunday.

03:00.440 --> 03:02.880
The parish will miss you.
When are you leaving?

03:02.880 --> 03:05.440
Well, running this
house of God's a full-time job.

03:05.440 --> 03:07.320
But I'll be close by if you need me.

03:07.320 --> 03:11.320
Hello, Donny. Is the snow
still good for packing, lad?

03:12.000 --> 03:14.240
Quite a hospital
you've built, father.

03:14.240 --> 03:17.360
Well, it's God's design, for sure.
But since he never went to

03:17.360 --> 03:20.120
architecture school, I had to
draw up the blueprints.

03:20.120 --> 03:24.120
Let's see you hit Flannery's pub
    across the street.

03:26.840 --> 03:29.640
Got it!

03:29.640 --> 03:33.640
Help, help, Father! Help!
This guy's hurt real bad, Father.

03:38.600 --> 03:42.600
Please don't let me die!

04:13.240 --> 04:17.240
We was moving a milling machine when
it fell over. Killed another fella.

04:17.399 --> 04:20.120
     Get me 15cc of cocaine solution,

04:20.120 --> 04:21.880
         cotton sutures and a needle.

04:21.880 --> 04:24.400
He's lost a lot of blood.
We'll hold him down.

04:24.400 --> 04:25.720
        It might be pretty painful. &gt;

04:25.720 --> 04:28.680
Patrick's Catholic, Father.
Could you say something?

04:28.680 --> 04:32.680
Just in case? &gt;

04:35.400 --> 04:39.400
(GIVES BLESSING IN LATIN)

05:02.680 --> 05:03.720
                                Jack.

05:03.720 --> 05:06.400
What?  I'm sorry.

05:06.400 --> 05:09.880
What? Did the police call
with some news about my son?

05:09.880 --> 05:12.840
                Pete's still missing.

05:12.840 --> 05:15.760
It's my fault he's been kidnapped.

05:15.760 --> 05:19.760
I should have pushed harder for a
daycare centre here at the hospital.

05:22.480 --> 05:26.480
Instead of passing Pete around...

05:26.760 --> 05:28.400
..for anybody to play with him.

05:28.400 --> 05:30.960
&lt; Assuming everybody
would be nice to him.

05:30.960 --> 05:34.960
I was out all night looking
for my son, going door to door.

05:35.680 --> 05:39.680
Handing out flyers
with Pete's picture on it.

05:39.720 --> 05:43.720
Why don't you give me a bunch?
I'll put some up in my neighbourhood.

05:44.800 --> 05:47.800
I'd really appreciate it.

05:47.800 --> 05:49.320
              How's Mr O'Casey doing?

05:49.320 --> 05:51.880
I still don't know yet.

05:51.880 --> 05:55.880
At least he's off the respirator
and he's got a partial return of
function in his legs.

05:56.280 --> 06:00.280
Jack. Don't sleep in this room.
It doesn't look good, OK?

06:16.320 --> 06:20.320
St Eligius' 50th anniversary is
turning out to be quite a shindig.

06:20.640 --> 06:24.160
I hope our hospital staff have
been co-operating with you on

06:24.160 --> 06:26.000
your oral retrospective.

06:26.000 --> 06:28.440
Well, it's been half-hearted at best.

06:28.440 --> 06:31.720
But since you've been here the
longest, the Historical Society is

06:31.720 --> 06:35.720
particularly interested
in your reminiscences.

06:35.760 --> 06:39.720
The sun was setting on
       the island of the rising sun.

06:39.720 --> 06:43.360
By leading the US forces
            in the invasion,

06:43.360 --> 06:46.000
McCarthy fulfilled his promise
      of "I shall return".

06:46.000 --> 06:48.960
Who shall ever forget the
magnificent image of the Marines

06:48.960 --> 06:51.320
planting the Stars and Stripes
      on Mt Suribachi?

06:51.320 --> 06:53.600
Excuse me, Dr Auschlander.

06:53.600 --> 06:54.640
Oh, yes.

06:54.640 --> 06:56.760
You need to speak
into the microphone.

06:56.760 --> 06:58.400
Yes, yes, of course.

06:58.400 --> 06:59.960
I always get carried away

06:59.960 --> 07:02.800
whenever I recall my Navy days
      in the Pacific theatre.

07:02.800 --> 07:06.800
Well, your work there
led you to be hired here
at St Eligius by Father McCabe.

07:06.960 --> 07:10.960
Yes. I arrived here
                 April 14th, 1945.

07:22.920 --> 07:26.920
Come in. &gt;

07:27.400 --> 07:28.440
Is this a bad time?

07:28.440 --> 07:30.120
Not at all, Daniel.

07:30.120 --> 07:32.440
I'm just reprimanding
this lad who was caught

07:32.440 --> 07:34.520
stealing a patient's pocketbook.

07:34.520 --> 07:36.560
What do you think
I should do to him?

07:36.560 --> 07:37.720
           Tan his hide.

07:37.720 --> 07:40.040
Oh, stay out of this, four eyes.

07:40.040 --> 07:41.960
Dr Daniel Auschlander, meet... &gt;

07:41.960 --> 07:44.040
Frankie Fish.

07:44.040 --> 07:46.360
..Donald Westphall.

07:46.360 --> 07:50.360
May I show you to your office?

08:05.440 --> 08:09.440
You'd better be sitting here when
I get back, or I'm coming after you.

08:16.760 --> 08:17.960
                     Father McCabe...

08:17.960 --> 08:20.440
Joseph. I can't tell you
how thrilled I am

08:20.440 --> 08:24.000
you're going to be working here.
St Eligius needs a liver specialist.

08:24.000 --> 08:28.000
Your studies in hepatic dysfunction
and tropical diseases in the South
Pacific are very impressive.

08:36.320 --> 08:40.320
Daniel, we'll talk later.
I want to get back to that boy
before he's sent to reform school.

09:04.600 --> 09:08.600
I love what you've done
with the place.

09:11.280 --> 09:14.640
This office could use
  a desk lamp and some pictures.

09:14.640 --> 09:16.440
Maybe even a record player.

09:16.440 --> 09:18.800
But I'll tell you
               what it really needs.

09:18.800 --> 09:21.000
A woman's delicate touch.

09:21.000 --> 09:24.600
What a line!
You must be fresh from the service.

09:24.600 --> 09:26.320
&lt; Here. This is for you.

09:26.320 --> 09:28.520
Heavily starched, thank you.

09:28.520 --> 09:29.800
      How do you find Boston?

09:29.800 --> 09:33.200
Take a left at Rhode Island!

09:33.200 --> 09:35.840
I haven't seen much
of the town really.

09:35.840 --> 09:37.680
Maybe you could show me
     around some time?

09:37.680 --> 09:39.360
Maybe you could show me
     around some time?
             Perhaps.

09:39.360 --> 09:43.360
         See you. Friend.

09:49.480 --> 09:50.680
What are we doing here?

09:50.680 --> 09:54.680
Since you won't listen
to reason, I thought I'd
          knock some sense into you.

09:57.680 --> 09:59.240
I ain't fighting a priest!

09:59.240 --> 10:02.960
Don't worry,
God won't hold it against you.

10:02.960 --> 10:05.240
Your father came by last week.

10:05.240 --> 10:08.000
He said you're getting to be
   a real pain in the keister.

10:08.000 --> 10:10.320
and you haven't been to
     church in nearly a year.

10:10.320 --> 10:13.280
No need to.
Not gonna make me a better person.

10:13.280 --> 10:15.560
Maybe not,
  but you haven't been going to

10:15.560 --> 10:18.440
school either. And for sure,
that will make you stupid.

10:18.440 --> 10:21.120
   What have I got be smart for?

10:21.120 --> 10:24.640
Life dealt me a crummy hand, so
what's the use? Why should I play?

10:24.640 --> 10:27.240
Stop feeling sorry for yourself.
Come on!

10:27.240 --> 10:30.520
     I ain't boxing with you.

10:30.520 --> 10:31.560
                Uh!

10:31.560 --> 10:35.320
You're going to run into pain and
disappointment your whole life.

10:35.320 --> 10:39.320
If you don't learn to face up
to it, you're going to get the tar
beat out of you every time.

10:40.120 --> 10:44.000
Now let's go.

10:44.000 --> 10:47.480
I know you love your family, Donald.
It must be ten years.

10:47.480 --> 10:51.480
Time to get on with your life.

10:59.560 --> 11:01.480
 There's no reason for what happened.

11:01.480 --> 11:03.120
Ah, it hurts growing up.

11:03.120 --> 11:04.920
                  I'll show you hurt!

11:04.920 --> 11:08.920
                   Die! Shut up. Die!

11:20.880 --> 11:22.200
                               Sorry.

11:22.200 --> 11:25.040
Have you looked through
             any mug shots?

11:25.040 --> 11:28.200
I only saw the back
of the guy's head.

11:28.200 --> 11:30.560
Maybe I should call
the police again.

11:30.560 --> 11:31.600
                       Jack, go home.

11:31.600 --> 11:35.400
I should have done something
for Pete. ID tags, fingerprints.

11:35.400 --> 11:38.160
   Jack, go home. I'll cover for you.

11:38.160 --> 11:40.480
Mr O'Casey, I still haven't
made the diagnosis.

11:40.480 --> 11:44.000
I thought it was meningitis till
he developed lower extremity paresis.

11:44.000 --> 11:46.840
Maybe you missed something
in the medical history.

11:46.840 --> 11:49.920
Mr O'Casey was pretty vague,
and his wife was even less help.

11:49.920 --> 11:51.480
Did you check the computer?

11:51.480 --> 11:53.320
Yeah, the records
only go back to '69.

11:53.320 --> 11:57.320
Well, this may come as a shock,
but there's a whole world
   that existed before floppy disks.

11:58.520 --> 12:02.480
Talk to Wayne in the basement
where all the back medical records
are in boxes.

12:02.480 --> 12:05.160
They're just sitting there,
waiting to be excavated.

12:05.160 --> 12:07.800
What do you mean,
I should go down there and

12:07.800 --> 12:10.080
dig around and try and...

12:10.080 --> 12:12.680
Try and uncover something?
Maybe I will.

12:12.680 --> 12:16.680
I'll call the police first.

12:22.320 --> 12:26.320
Do you think the cops
will ever find Jack's kid?

12:26.320 --> 12:29.920
Not a chance.

12:29.920 --> 12:32.200
&lt; Strong, Patrick, a real scrapper.

12:32.200 --> 12:35.800
&lt; Not many men get crushed
by a heavy machine and live
to tell the tale.

12:35.800 --> 12:38.120
&lt; The doctor says
I'm going to be fine.

12:38.120 --> 12:40.960
Patrick's worked in the mills
since he was 12.

12:40.960 --> 12:43.520
            Sometimes 18 hours a day.

12:43.520 --> 12:47.360
Trying to earn enough money
so we can get married.

12:47.360 --> 12:51.360
But if this is what wanting
a life together costs,
it is not worth the price.

12:51.920 --> 12:54.200
Alison, you can't think like that.

12:54.200 --> 12:55.880
America was built on hard work.

12:55.880 --> 12:59.840
Little by little we come closer
to the happiness my father
 came searching for.

12:59.840 --> 13:02.520
       Patrick. I love you.

13:02.520 --> 13:05.680
          But I'm afraid.

13:05.680 --> 13:09.680
I don't want us to start off
on the wrong foot, with no money.

13:09.720 --> 13:11.440
    I don't even have a dowry.

13:11.440 --> 13:13.400
We have each other.

13:13.400 --> 13:17.080
That will be enough.

13:17.080 --> 13:21.080
Father McCabe. Will you
       perform the wedding ceremony?

13:21.080 --> 13:25.080
When you're back on your feet, lad,
then you two come and see me.

13:31.920 --> 13:33.040
                         Dr Morrison.

13:33.040 --> 13:34.880
   Have you seen my mother any place?

13:34.880 --> 13:36.080
No, I'm afraid not.

13:36.080 --> 13:37.600
                     How's my father?

13:37.600 --> 13:41.600
Well, he's gotten back
some motor function in his legs
but he's still heavily sedated.

13:42.040 --> 13:45.120
So even when he wakes up,
conversation won't make much sense.

13:45.120 --> 13:47.400
                   Nothing new there.

13:47.400 --> 13:50.240
Kevin.

13:50.240 --> 13:54.120
Your anger is not going to
help your father get better.

13:54.120 --> 13:55.160
                             So what?

13:55.160 --> 13:58.440
He's done nothing but shove me out
of his life for the past two years.

13:58.440 --> 14:02.040
I came in yesterday, he didn't want
anything to do with me. You know why?

14:02.040 --> 14:06.040
                     Because I'm gay.

14:12.800 --> 14:16.800
My father acted as though my
homosexuality was an act of defiance.

14:17.920 --> 14:20.520
He took it personally.

14:20.520 --> 14:24.520
Rather than being glad that I was
finally happy with who I am,

14:25.440 --> 14:29.440
he stopped loving me.

14:29.680 --> 14:33.680
I became the son he never had.

14:34.240 --> 14:37.880
Kevin.

14:37.880 --> 14:41.880
Fathers and sons, they lose
each other for all kinds of reasons.

14:42.880 --> 14:46.880
Some get pushed away, some...

14:47.120 --> 14:51.120
If you want
         the relationship to last...

14:51.280 --> 14:54.320
..you have got to say
the things you feel now.

14:54.320 --> 14:55.920
Good or bad.

14:55.920 --> 14:59.880
Because someday you'll reach out

14:59.880 --> 15:03.880
and your dad won't be there.

15:14.600 --> 15:17.080
You promised me the roof
     would last a lifetime!

15:17.080 --> 15:21.080
Ten years is a very short life,
 wouldn't you say?

15:21.200 --> 15:24.560
No, I'm expecting you to come back
and fix what should have been taken

15:24.560 --> 15:28.080
care of when you
built this hospital!

15:28.080 --> 15:30.040
Well, what about craftsmanship?

15:30.040 --> 15:34.040
Have you no pride in your work?

15:34.760 --> 15:38.760
Well, when can you come back
and make the necessary repairs?

15:38.920 --> 15:42.920
Waiting until hell freezes over
is an ecumenical nonsense!

15:45.680 --> 15:49.680
Don't say it.

15:51.120 --> 15:54.880
I should have been more tactful.

15:54.880 --> 15:56.080
It's not going to work.

15:56.080 --> 15:59.800
The hospital's had financial
trouble before. I'll raise

15:59.800 --> 16:02.680
the money for the new roof,
bake sales or bingo or somehow.

16:02.680 --> 16:05.600
I'm referring to myself here.
It won't work.

16:05.600 --> 16:08.120
Why are you always running off
when I want to talk?

16:08.120 --> 16:09.800
We're talking. But I'm late for

16:09.800 --> 16:12.040
the meeting with
        the new cardinal. Hold that.

16:12.040 --> 16:15.040
A swastika and the word kike
are painted on my office wall.

16:15.040 --> 16:17.720
If that's the way people round here
feel about me, fine.

16:17.720 --> 16:19.760
I can catch the 8:00
back to New York City.

16:19.760 --> 16:21.000
Daniel, you can't leave.

16:21.000 --> 16:22.040
                            Watch me.

16:22.040 --> 16:24.560
Oh, come on!
First incident, you're going to run?

16:24.560 --> 16:28.320
Just a month ago I was
to be named at the Board of
Medical Quality Assurance.

16:28.320 --> 16:31.160
Underqualified, they said.
Too Semitic was the truth.

16:31.160 --> 16:35.160
If we don't stand up to hatred
and fear, it spreads. It kills.

16:35.560 --> 16:39.480
In the Army I was in a platoon.
It was the American melting pot.

16:39.480 --> 16:43.480
Some southerner asked me
why I was defending America
as if it wasn't my country.

16:43.560 --> 16:46.080
And my family has been here
for over 100 years.

16:46.080 --> 16:48.520
Well, I told that hick my grandfather

16:48.520 --> 16:51.920
fought for the North in the Civil
War. Then we got into fisticuffs.

16:51.920 --> 16:55.000
Before being drafted, I lost
my fiancee as she was a gentile.

16:55.000 --> 16:56.640
I need you here, Daniel.

16:56.640 --> 16:59.000
You and I can make the difference.

16:59.000 --> 17:02.960
If we don't leave this world in a
better shape than when we got here,

17:02.960 --> 17:06.800
what's the point?

17:06.800 --> 17:07.920
THUNDER RUMBLES

17:07.920 --> 17:11.240
Rain depresses some people.

17:11.240 --> 17:13.400
                              Not me.

17:13.400 --> 17:15.319
Don't go anywhere until I get back.

17:15.319 --> 17:19.319
Please.

17:28.240 --> 17:29.280
Excuse me.

17:29.280 --> 17:30.440
Doctor. Doctor.

17:30.440 --> 17:33.080
My name's Patrick O'Casey.
My daughter's in there.

17:33.080 --> 17:35.480
She was brought in two days ago.
I have to see her.

17:35.480 --> 17:38.280
You can't, not until
she's allowed out of isolation.

17:38.280 --> 17:41.080
Patrick just got home last night.

17:41.080 --> 17:44.360
He hasn't seen Sarah since he left
for Fort Bragg eight months ago.

17:44.360 --> 17:48.360
All right. But you'll have to wait
here because of the risk to the baby.

17:52.800 --> 17:56.800
You'll have to be content
with looking at her
through this window for now.

17:57.280 --> 17:58.800
                     Can you see her?

17:58.800 --> 18:02.520
Yes, there she is.
That's Sarah, the one with the doll.

18:02.520 --> 18:04.200
What's going to happen to her?

18:04.200 --> 18:05.840
You really should
speak with her physician.

18:05.840 --> 18:07.840
You really should
speak with her physician.
Tell me!

18:07.840 --> 18:10.760
Well, poliomyelitis attacks
the spinal cord and brain.

18:10.760 --> 18:14.760
The muscle groups are destroyed.
Many children recover entirely,
others can only move an arm or a leg.

18:15.760 --> 18:19.760
And some die.

18:23.040 --> 18:25.320
Am I going to lose my little girl?

18:25.320 --> 18:28.960
The wonder of medicine, Mr O'Casey,
is it is unpredictable.

18:28.960 --> 18:31.880
You and your wife have to be strong.

18:31.880 --> 18:34.880
Your daughter needs to know
that you haven't given up,

18:34.880 --> 18:38.880
despite overwhelming adversity.

18:38.880 --> 18:40.320
Good news.

18:40.320 --> 18:44.320
I've been reading and re-reading
your family's history, trying

18:44.400 --> 18:48.240
to find some clue, a connection
to his symptoms, and suddenly,

18:48.240 --> 18:50.160
there it was.

18:50.160 --> 18:54.160
Mr O'Casey's sister Sarah
died of polio in 1955.

18:54.920 --> 18:58.920
She'd never been vaccinated.
And Mr O'Casey never received
proper immunisation.

19:00.560 --> 19:01.920
          He's got polio?

19:01.920 --> 19:05.920
Come on, Dr Morrison, this is 1986.
It's like saying he's
 a victim of the bubonic plague.

19:06.680 --> 19:09.280
In the '50s a lot of kids
were vaccinated with

19:09.280 --> 19:11.040
what's called a dead virus.

19:11.040 --> 19:15.040
But it only worked temporarily.
People like your father,
who were never followed up

19:15.680 --> 19:19.680
with booster injections,
lost immunity to polio
and are still susceptible.

19:20.000 --> 19:21.960
Jack.

19:21.960 --> 19:22.960
         Is there a cure?

19:22.960 --> 19:26.920
         Is there a cure?
Um... No, no.

19:26.920 --> 19:30.920
But the infection will eventually
dissipate and, with time and help

19:31.280 --> 19:35.280
from you both, he should be fine.

19:35.960 --> 19:38.720
How do you know?
My aunt died of polio.

19:38.720 --> 19:41.760
In cases like your father's
where there's been an early

19:41.760 --> 19:43.720
return of motor function,

19:43.720 --> 19:47.720
there's usually a full recovery.

19:49.560 --> 19:50.000
What is it?

19:50.000 --> 19:52.560
What is it?
The police called,
they think they found your son.

19:52.560 --> 19:53.000
